'''Marojejy National Park''' is a [[national park]] in the [[SAVA Region]] of northeastern [[Madagascar]]. It covers {{convert|55,500|ha|sqmi|abbr=on}} and is centered around the [[Marojejy Massif]], a mountain chain which rises to an elevation of {{convert|2132|m|ft|abbr=on}}.  Access to the area around the [[massif]] was restricted to only research scientists when the site was set aside as a strict [[nature reserve]] in 1952.  In 1998, it was opened to the public when it was converted into a national park.  It became part of the [[World Heritage Site]] known as the [[Rainforests of the Atsinanana]] in 2007.  Despite its rugged terrain, [[poaching]] and [[Selection cutting|selective logging]] are still persistent problems, particularly since the start of the [[2009 Malagasy political crisis|2009 political crisis in Madagascar]].  Mining, [[slash and burn]] agriculture, and wood collection also pose threats to the park and its wildlife.

The wide range of elevations and rugged topology of the massif create diverse habitats that transition quickly with changes in altitude.  Warm, dense [[rainforest]] can be found at lower elevations, followed by shorter forests at higher elevations, followed still by [[cloud forest]], and topped near the peaks with the only remaining undisturbed mountain [[Shrubland|scrub]] in Madagascar.  Better growing conditions for plants can be found on the eastern side of the mountain, which receives more rain than the western side.  This habitat diversity lends itself to high levels of [[biodiversity]].  At least 118&nbsp;species of bird, 148&nbsp;species of reptile and amphibian, and 11&nbsp;species of [[lemur]] are known to occur within Marojejy National Park.  One of the lemurs, the [[silky sifaka]] (''Propithecus candidus'') is listed among "[[The World's 25 Most Endangered Primates]]".  The [[Helmet Vanga]] (''Euryceros prevostii'') is considered the iconic bird species of the park.

One path leads from the entrance of the park to the summit.  There are three camps along the route: Camp Mantella at {{convert|450|m|ft|abbr=on}} in elevation in lowland rainforest, Camp Marojejia at {{convert|775|m|ft|abbr=on}} at the transition between lowland and montane rain forest, and Camp Simpona at {{convert|1250|m|ft|abbr=on}} in the middle of the montane rainforest.  Camp Simpona acts as a [[Mountaineering#Base Camp|base camp]] for the trek to the summit, a route that stretches {{convert|2|km|mi|abbr=on}} and can take up to four or five hours.

==History==
Marojejy National Park is located in the northeast of Madagascar between the towns of [[Andapa]] and [[Sambava]]{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=2}} and extends approximately {{convert|32|km|mi|abbr=on}} from east to west and {{convert|22|km|mi|abbr=on}} from north to south.{{Sfn|Goodman|2000|p=14}}  It is centered around the chain of mountains known as [[Marojejy Massif]].{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=2}}  Despite a scientific survey of some of the other mountains in the region by the 1929 [[Mission Zoologique Franco-Anglo-Am<U+00E9>ricaine]],{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1452}} Marojejy was not surveyed until 1937 when L.-J. Arragon of the Service G<U+00E9>ographique de Madagascar ascended [[Marojejy Est]]. Arragon did not conduct any field research during his visit.{{Sfn|Evans|1990|p=15}}  The massif was not geologically described until after the French [[Botany|botanist]] [[Henri Jean Humbert]] from the [[Mus<U+00E9>um national d'histoire naturelle|National Museum of Natural History in Paris]] explored the mountains in 1948.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=2}}{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1452}}  Humbert had previously explored numerous mountain ranges in continental Africa before coming to Marojejy.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=2}} Between November 1948 and November 1950, he spent five months collecting 4,039&nbsp;dried plant ([[herbarium]]) specimens for study.{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1452}}  After several expeditions, he published the book "A Marvel of Nature" in 1955, in which he claimed the [[massif]] was the most impressive range in all of Madagascar because of its size, floral diversity, and pristine natural state.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=2}}{{Sfn|Humbert|1955|p=7}}

Marojejy was set aside as one of Madagascar's strict nature reserves in 1952 largely due to Humbert's enthusiasm and support.  Under this protection, only research scientists were permitted to visit the site.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=2}}{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1452}}  In 1998, Marojejy was converted into a national park and became open to visitors as a result.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=2}}

Originally seen as a [[transitional zone]] between the eastern rainforests and the [[Central Highlands (Madagascar)|central highlands]], it is now recognized as having its own unique features, with some of the richest [[biodiversity]] on the island.{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1451}}  Several studies from the early 1970s through the 1990s surveyed the mountain ecosystems and inventoried the flora and fauna.{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|pp=1452<U+2013>1453}}  In 2007, Marojejy was listed as a [[World Heritage Site]] as part of the [[Rainforests of the Atsinanana]].<ref name=2007IUCN_Eval1257/> Due to [[Illegal logging in Madagascar|illegal logging]] and trafficking of valuable hardwoods, and especially after the [[2009 Malagasy political crisis|2009 political crisis in Madagascar]], the Rainforests of the Atsinanana was added to the [[list of World Heritage in Danger]] in 2010.<ref name=WHC/>

===Park boundaries and size===
[[File:Marojejy Map 2011.png|thumb|right|alt=Map of showing contour lines, forest cover in two shades (virgin vs. degraded), the trail from the visitor center, and the road and nearby towns.|Map of Marojejy National Park]]
The boundaries of Marojejy National Park were originally established by approximation when the park was established in 1952.  With a second decree (no. 66-242) from the [[Politics of Madagascar|government of Madagascar]] in 1966, the park's status as a strict nature reserve was reaffirmed, and its boundaries were marked by 89 points.  From these markers, the size of the park was estimated at {{convert|60150|ha|sqmi|abbr=on}}.  At the time, two families were living {{convert|450|m|ft|abbr=on}} inside the park boundaries, which initially was permitted under the conditions that they did not extend their cultivated land into the park or allow others to join them.  The families were later expelled for violating these conditions.  Many families from the local communities did not understand why such a large area so rich in resources and necessary for their survival was forbidden to them, and between the late 1980s and 1993, they stopped honoring the status of the park.  They began clearing the outer edges of the reserve to start plantations of [[vanilla]] and [[coffee]].  In 1993, the [[World Wide Fund for Nature]] (WWF) and the Service des Eaux et For<U+00EA>ts renewed conservation efforts in the area, evicted the people living inside the reserve, and renegotiated the borders with the local community, based on the 1966 decree.  Trails and posts were then used to clearly mark the edges of the reserve.{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|pp=1453<U+2013>1454}}  In the years following these events, many communities living near the borders of the park have become more involved in forest surveillance, and deforestation has fallen off sharply to only a few [[hectare]]s a year.{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|pp=1456<U+2013>1457}}

In 1998, the WWF requested that the government of Madagascar relax the restrictions on the reserve to allow for [[ecotourism]], the revenue from which could benefit the people living in the periphery of the park.  With a decree (no. 98-375) in May 1998, the reserve became a national park.  The boundaries were renegotiated, particularly in the western and northwestern regions of the park, and this time using clear natural landmarks, such as ridge crests, as markers.  The size of the park was adjusted to {{convert|60050|ha|sqmi|abbr=on}}, with some western communities gaining access to untouched forest zones while communities in the northwest lost agricultural land.  Approximately {{convert|5000|ha|sqmi|abbr=on}} had been illegally cleared within the park and are still part of the park.  There are now 91&nbsp;boundary markers and the boundaries are [[georeference]]d.  Intermediate boundary markers are placed between existing markers to demarcate the edges of the park during disputes with the local community.{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1454}}

During October 2005, reports surfaced showing that boundary markers were being moved with the approval of park employees and that areas within the park were being cleared for agriculture.  In January 2006, the Park Logistics Coordinator was fired for moving boundary markers while employed as the Park Conservation Agent and selling the {{convert|9|ha|sqmi|abbr=on}} of park land to a local farmer for 2&nbsp;million [[Malagasy franc]]s (~{{US$|200}}).<ref name=Marojejy_News/>  In 2010, a new demarcation adjusted the size the park down to {{convert|55500|ha|sqmi|abbr=on}}.<ref name=MNP_Marojejy/>

==Topography and habitat==
[[File:Summit 01.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Three side-by-side mountain peaks, as viewed from the summit of Marojejy Massif.|View of the surrounding mountains from the summit of Marojejy Massif at {{convert|2132|m|ft|abbr=on}}]]
Marojejy National Park covers {{convert|55,500|ha|sqmi|abbr=on}} and protects almost the entire massif, which ranges in elevation from {{convert|75|m|ft|abbr=on}} to {{convert|2132|m|ft|abbr=on}} at the summit.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=2}}{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1454}}{{Sfn|Safford|Duckworth|1990|p=5}}  The massif is part of a [[Mountain range|mountain chain]] that stretches from [[Tsaratanana]] in the northwest to the [[Masoala Peninsula]] in the south.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=13}}  The crests of the massif form an east<U+2013>west line with a series of distinct peaks along its irregular structure, which consists of parallel or divergent crest lines broken apart by steep and irregular slopes.{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1454}}  Rising {{convert|2000|m|ft|abbr=on}} over as little as {{convert|8|km|mi|abbr=on}}, the Marojejy Massif has some of the most precipitous terrain in Madagascar.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=13}} As a result of this sharp rise in elevation and rugged [[topography]], it has a variety of [[microclimate]]s and a visible change in habitat,{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=3}}{{Sfn|Preston-Mafham|1991|p=213}} making it one of the few places in the world where [[Cloud forest|cloud-covered rainforest]] rapidly transitions to high mountain tundra over a distance that can be covered on foot.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=2}}  Also due to the rugged topography, the vegetative mosaic varies between the crests and slopes of the massif, even at the same elevations.  For example, crests and adjoining slopes often have less than 20% of their flowering plant species in common.{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1458}}

Temperatures in the region are fairly constant, with both the daily temperature range and the seasonal range varying only slightly.  February is the hottest month, averaging {{convert|25|C|F|abbr=on}}, while August is the coolest, averaging {{convert|19|C|F|abbr=on}}.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=13}}  Climbing the peaks, temperature decreases by {{convert|1|C-change|sigfig=2|abbr=on}} per {{convert|200|m|ft|abbr=on}} of increased altitude, and temperatures on the summit decline to {{convert|1.5|C|F|abbr=on}} in July.{{Sfn|Safford|Duckworth|1990b|p=17}}  The [[relative humidity]] for the region hovers around 87% throughout most of the year, although it rises to 97% between March and April.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=13}}  Rain falls every month on the southern side of the mountain, with the region receiving at least {{convert|2300|mm|in|abbr=on}} of rain annually,{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1454}} making it one of the wettest areas in Madagascar.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=13}}{{Sfn|Preston-Mafham|1991|p=213}}  The northern side of the mountain is more tropical, with a 6-month dry season, and receives about {{convert|1500|mm|in|abbr=on}} of rain per year.{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1454}}  The general region receives the most rainfall during the warm season, from November through April, when heavy rain and occasional [[cyclone]]s are delivered from the northwest by [[monsoon]]s.  During the cooler season, between May and October, lighter rains are delivered by winds from the southeast.

[[File:Marojejy NP 2009.ogv|thumbtime=76|thumb|350px|right|Landscape and wildlife of Marojejy National Park]]
Both temperature and rainfall vary significantly by location within the park.  Lower temperatures are found at higher elevations,{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=13}} and the eastern slopes of the massif receive the most of the rainfall, since the western slopes lie in the [[rain shadow]] of the mountain and consequently experience a prolonged dry period.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=13}}{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=3}}  The tops of the ridges experience strong winds and offer poor soil conditions.  The effect can be seen in the plant life and their growth rates.  The wide range in elevations and the rugged topography also play a crucial role in creation of the varied habitats distributed across the mountain slopes by affecting [[Temperature|air temperature]], fluctuations in temperature, and humidity levels.  The interplay between these factors impacts the growth and development of plants, which form the foundation of the ecosystem.  The result is an extremely varied and unevenly distributed forest that covers 90% of the park.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=3}}

The mountains of both Marojejy and nearby [[Anjanaharibe-Sud Reserve|Anjanaharibe-Sud Special Reserve]] feed several [[drainage basin]]s, including the [[Lokoho River]], which is sourced from the western and southern slopes of Marojejy, and the [[Androranga River]], which originates from the northern slopes of Marojejy.  Both rivers travel towards Sambava and drain into the [[Indian Ocean]].{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=13}}  Marojejy is connected to the Anjanaharibe-Sud Special Reserve by the [[Betaolana corridor]], a narrow mid-elevation strip of forest extending west and slightly south.{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|pp=1451<U+2013>1452}}

===Geology===
[[File:Ambatotsondrona 03.jpg|thumb|left|alt=A steep cliff partly blanketed in forest looms over the forests below.|The cliff named Ambatotsondrona, like the rest of the highest peaks at Marojejy, is composed mostly of [[gneiss]] rock.]]
As with the rest of Madagascar, the rocks of Marojejy National Park were once part of the [[supercontinent]] of [[Gondwana]], which began to break up 160&nbsp;million years ago to form the southern continents.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=14}}  However, the [[bedrock]] of Marojejy formed over 500&nbsp;million years ago during the [[Precambrian]] beneath an ancient mountain range that has since eroded away completely.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=13}}{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=14}}  The bedrock is composed mostly of [[Granite|granitic]] rocks, although it also contains a significant amount of [[gneiss]],{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1454}}{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=13}}{{Sfn|Goodman|2000|p=15}} a [[Ore|high-grade]] [[metamorphic rock]] that formed under high pressure and temperature deep beneath the ancient mountain range.  In places where heat and pressure were highest, the rock melted completely and eventually recrystallized at depth as granite, an [[igneous rock]].{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=14}}  Later, [[Vein (geology)|veins]] of [[quartz]] formed in cracks in the bedrock; these are the source of the [[quartz]] and [[amethyst]] crystals mined in the region today.  In more recent geological times, the area's abundant [[quartzite]] formed when quartz-rich sands were deposited on the bedrock, and were then buried and recrystallized ([[Metamorphism|metamorphosed]]).{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=14}}  The [[soil pH]] is expected to be acidic to neutral.{{Sfn|Safford|1990|p=19}}

The highest, most rugged peaks of Marojejy owe their form to the gneiss from which they are made.  The gneiss consists of alternating bands of light and dark colored minerals.  The light minerals, consisting mostly of quartz and [[feldspar]], are the hardest and most resistant, whereas the dark minerals, which are mostly [[biotite|biotite mica]] and [[hornblende]], are softer and weather out faster.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=14}}  This layered composition, in combination with the north-facing 45-degree angle at which the rocks are tilted, accounts for the asymmetric character of the peaks.  The northern slopes dip moderately, while the southern faces are typically near-vertical cliffs where the rocks fractured counter to the layered grain.{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1454}}{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=14}}  The cliff named Ambatotsondrona, with its sheer, south-facing rock wall, is an example.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=14}}

==Biodiversity==
[[File:Helmet Vanga 05.jpg|thumb|right|alt=An orange and black bird with a bright blue beak places food in the open mouth of one of the three chicks in her nest.|The [[Helmet Vanga]] is the iconic bird species of Marojejy National Park.]]
Marojejy National Park is noted for its rich biodiversity, which can appeal to both scientist and ecotourist.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=2}}{{Sfn|Patel|2007|p=11}}  There are a wide range of habitats within the park, and many of its plants and animals are [[Endemism|endemic]] to the area.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=3}}  Scientific expeditions regularly discover species that are either not previously documented in Marojejy, or in some cases, completely new to science.  Some new species are highly [[Endangered species|endangered]].  In the case of many large groups, such as [[invertebrate]]s, very little is known and much remains to be discovered.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=4}}

===Flora===
The vegetation of Marojejy National Park is extremely diverse due to the various microclimates.  The microclimates also affect plant growth rates, with the wet eastern slopes showing faster plant growth, the dry western slopes exhibiting slower plant growth, and the plants on the ridge tops hindered by high winds and poor soils.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=3}}  More than 2,000&nbsp; species of [[flowering plant]]s (angiosperms) have been discovered at the park so far.{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1454}}  At least four plant [[Family (biology)|families]] are found at all elevations: [[Clusiaceae]] and [[Poaceae]] are generally common, while [[Myrsinaceae]] and [[Elaeocarpaceae]] are rare.{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1455}}

There are four basic types of forest found at Marojejy:{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1454}}{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=3}}

* '''Lowland rainforest''': Below {{convert|800|m|ft|abbr=on}},{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1454}}{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=3}} species diversity is the highest{{Sfn|Preston-Mafham|1991|p=213}} due to abundant rainfall, consistently warm weather, and protection from strong winds.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=3}}  The [[canopy (biology)|canopy]] of the [[Old-growth forest|primary forest]]s is dense with tall trees reaching heights of {{convert|25|<U+2013>|35|m|ft|abbr=on}}.{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1454}}{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=3}}  Many [[Trunk (botany)|tree trunks]] measure over {{convert|30|cm|in|abbr=on}} in diameter.{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1454}}  A great variety of [[palm (plant)|palm]]s, [[epiphyte]]s, and [[fern]]s are also present,{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=3}} with 130&nbsp;species of fern known from this zone.{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1454}}  [[Secondary growth]], which primarily includes bamboo, wild ginger or ''longoza'' (genus ''[[Aframomum]]''), and Traveller's Palm (''[[Ravenala madagascariensis]]''), is found in disturbed areas.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=3}}{{Sfn|Safford|1990|p=20}}  The most common families of flowering plant are [[Sapotaceae]], [[Rubiaceae]], [[Euphorbiaceae]], and [[Myrsinaceae]].  The most common families of plants in the light [[groundcover]] are Poaceae, [[Labiaceae]], [[Acanthaceae]], [[Gesneriaceae]], [[Melastomataceae]], and [[Balsaminaceae]].  The lowland rainforest region covers 38% of the surface area of the park.{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1454}}

[[File:Summit 02.jpg|thumb|right|alt=A view from the summit show the surrounding mountains and shorter vegetation|Sclerophyllous montane cloudforest, as seen from the summit, has shorter trees than the forests in the lowland areas.]]
* '''Moist montane rainforest''': Between {{convert|800|and|1400|m|ft|abbr=on}} and also covering 38% of the surface area of the park,{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1454}}{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=3}} trees and shrubs become increasingly smaller due to lower temperatures and poorer soils,{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=3}} and [[Cyatheales|tree fern]]s become more abundant as elevation increases.{{Sfn|Preston-Mafham|1991|p=213}}  The lower temperatures cause moisture to condense onto surfaces without forming mist.{{Sfn|Safford|2000|p=20}}  The transition between the lowland rainforests and the mid-altitude rainforest is gradual.{{Sfn|Preston-Mafham|1991|p=213}}  The canopy reaches heights of {{convert|18|<U+2013>|25|m|ft|abbr=on}},{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1454}}{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=3}} and sun-loving epiphytes, shrubs, and other forest floor species take advantage of the elevated light levels.  The increased humidity also favors [[moss]]es and ferns.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=3}}  The families Rubiaceae, Euphorbiaceae, [[Myrtaceae]], [[Arecaceae]], [[Pandanaceae]], and [[Burseraceae]] are the most common in this zone.{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1454}}

* '''Sclerophyllous montane cloudforest''': At {{convert|1400|to|1800|m|ft|abbr=on}} and covering 11.5% of the surface area of the park, the trees are significantly shorter, gnarled and stunted, with the canopy extending to a maximum height of only {{convert|10|or|15|m|ft|abbr=on}}.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=3}}{{Sfn|Preston-Mafham|1991|p=213}}{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|pp=1454<U+2013>1455}}  The most common plant families are [[Lauraceae]], Rubiaceae, Clusiaceae, and [[Araliaceae]].{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|pp=1454<U+2013>1455}}  The ground layer in the [[cloud forest]] is rich, and moss and [[lichen]] drape the branches of the trees.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=3}}{{Sfn|Preston-Mafham|1991|p=213}}  At least 122&nbsp;species of fern are found in this zone.{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|pp=1454<U+2013>1455}}  Temperatures are lower, and heavy clouds brought in by eastern winds blanket the forest.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=3}}  Endemism is very high at this altitude, particularly between the various peaks due to long isolation.  The area is also highly susceptible to fire due to its thick layer of [[humus]].{{Sfn|Safford|2000|pp=20<U+2013>21}}

* '''Montane scrub''': Above {{convert|1800|m|ft|abbr=on}} on only 1.5% of the surface area of the park, the last remaining mountain [[Shrubland|scrub]] in Madagascar can be found.  Unlike all other high mountain scrub on the island, it has not been altered by fire.{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1454}}{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=3}}  The region has an open, [[tundra]]-like cover, over thin, rocky soils.  Soil conditions, along with the cool temperatures, windy conditions, and low rainfall limits the vegetation,{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=3}} which reaches a maximum height of {{convert|2|m|ft|abbr=on}}.{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1455}}  Low, dense thickets of shrubs dominate, although terrestrial [[orchid]]s and miniature palms and bamboos are also present.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=3}}  The dominant families of plant are Poaceae, [[Ericaceae]], [[Asteraceae]], [[Balsaminaceae]], [[Cunoniaceae]], and Clusiaceae.{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1455}}

Of the many plant species found in Marojejy, 35 are palms, several of which are [[critically endangered]] and have extremely low populations.  Only three of these palm species can be found outside of Madagascar, and seven can only be found at Marojejy.  More than 275&nbsp;fern species are present in the rainforests of the massif, 18 of which are tree ferns and seven are found only at Marojejy.  Many of these fern species are very rare and have highly restricted distributions.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=4}}

Marojejy also contains several types of rare [[rosewood]] and palisandre (genus ''[[Dalbergia]]''), all of which are endemic to Madagascar.{{Sfn|Patel|2007|p=11}}  Rosewood, or ''andramena'' in Malagasy, is a type of hardwood with a lustrous deep red color, while palisandre, such as ''[[Dalbergia madagascariensis]]'', lacks the red color.  Of the three species of ''Dalbergia'' found in Marojejy, ''D.&nbsp;madagascariensis'' and ''[[Dalbergia baronii|D.&nbsp;baronii]]'' are listed as "[[Vulnerable species|vulnerable]]" on the [[IUCN Red List]], while ''[[Dalbergia louvelii|D.&nbsp;louvelii]]'' is listed as "[[Endangered species|endangered]]."  The park has few large specimens of the former two due to [[overexploitation]], and specimens are rarely found in the surrounding {{convert|5|km|mi|abbr=on}} surrounding the park.  The latter, ''D.&nbsp;louvelii'', is not found outside of the park.{{Sfn|Patel|2007|p=12}}

===Fauna===
[[File:Terpsiphone mutata 001.jpg|thumb|right|alt=A small bird with a short, thin beak, long tail feathers, a black head, and a blue eye-ring sits in a nest.|The [[Madagascar Paradise-flycatcher]] is one of many species of bird found at Marojejy.]]
Marojejy National Park is best known for its two iconic species, the [[Helmet Vanga]] (''Euryceros prevostii''){{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1454}}{{Sfn|Bradt|2007|p=345}} and the critically endangered [[silky sifaka]] or ''simpona'' (''Propithecus candidus'').{{Sfn|Preston-Mafham|1991|p=213}}{{Sfn|Patel|2007|p=11}}{{LoM3 Sfn|page=655}}  The silky sifaka has been listed as one of "[[The World's 25 Most Endangered Primates]]" since the inception of the list in 2000.{{Sfn|Patel|2009|pp=23<U+2013>26}}  According to estimates, fewer than 1,000 individuals of this species remain, and none exist in captivity.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=4}}

The wealth of species of well-known groups of animals demonstrates the depth of the biodiversity found at Marojejy National Park.  For example, 75 of the 118&nbsp;species of [[bird]]s (64%) found in or around Marojejy are forest-dwelling birds, a total that surpasses any other mountain site in Madagascar.  All of these forest-dependent bird species are endemic to Madagascar and utilize the forest for some portion of their life-cycle.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=3}}  One of these birds is the [[Madagascar Serpent-eagle]] (''Eutriorchis astur''),{{Sfn|Preston-Mafham|1991|p=213}} which prior to being reported in 1990, had not been seen by [[ornithologist]]s since 1932.{{Sfn|Safford|Duckworth|1990|p=5}}

In addition to the silky sifaka, Marojejy is home to 10 other species of [[lemur]],{{Sfn|Patel|2007|p=11}}{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=4}}{{LoM3 Sfn|page=655}} several of which are also endangered due mainly to [[habitat loss]].  The nocturnal [[aye-aye]] has only been seen once at the park, although one old nest and traces of its feeding have been found at various elevations.{{Sfn|Sterling|McFadden|2000|pp=269<U+2013>270}}  Other mammals include at least 15&nbsp;species of [[Tenrecidae|tenrec]],{{Sfn|Goodman|Jenkins|2000|p=201}} seven species of native [[rodent]],{{Sfn|Carleton|Goodman|2000|p=231}} the [[Fossa (animal)|fossa]] (''Cryptoprocta ferox''),{{Sfn|Patel|2009|p=24}} and the [[Madagascar Sucker-footed Bat]] (''Myzopoda aurita''){{Sfn|Safford|Duckworth|1990|p=5}}

The [[reptile]] and [[amphibian]] diversity at Marojejy is also rich, higher than any other protected area in Madagascar.  A total of 148&nbsp;species have been inventoried, and 17 of these are found only in Marojejy,{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=4}} including ''[[Brookesia karchei]]'' and ''[[Chamaeleo peyrieresi]]'', two species of several [[chameleon]]s found there.{{Sfn|Preston-Mafham|1991|p=213}}  The [[panther chameleon]] (''Furcifer pardalis''), leaf-tailed geckos (genus ''[[Uroplatus]]''), and many species of frogs are also reported from this locality.  Invertebrates include large [[millipede]]s, [[spider]]s, and an abundance of small [[leech]]es.{{Sfn|Bradt|2007|p=343}}

