==Camps and accommodations==
{{multiple image
| align     = right
| direction = horizontal
| footer    = Marojejy has one trail leading to the summit, with three camps, including Camp Marojejia (left), and views of geological features, such as Ambatotsondrona (right), covered in virgin rain forest.
| image1    = Camp Marojejia 01.jpg
| width1    = 175
| alt1      = A camp is nestled in tropic rain forest, with a steep mountain peek directly behind it.
| image2    = Ambatotsondrona 02.jpg
| width2    = 175
| alt2      = A large rock outcrop, partly covered by forest can be seen above the trees and clouds in the foreground.
}}

Marojejy National Park is open all year, with [[Bradt Travel Guides]] recommending April to May and September to December as the best times to visit due to less rainfall.{{Sfn|Bradt|2007|p=345}}{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=5}}  The park is one of the only [[List of national parks of Madagascar|national parks in Madagascar]] offering wooden chalets or bungalows, in addition to having a kitchen and toilet facilities at each of its three main camps inside a primary rainforest.{{Sfn|Bradt|2007|p=345}}{{LoM3 Sfn|page=656}}  The housing provides beds and basic bedding, while the kitchen and eating areas are covered and offer basic cooking utensils.  These three camps have basic tent sites for campers.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=5}}{{LoM3 Sfn|page=656}}  Tent campsites are also offered outside the park, while the only other overnight accommodations outside the park are in Andapa and Sambava.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=5}}  The park is unable to accommodate large groups.{{Sfn|Bradt|2007|p=344}}  Because of the rugged terrain and variable temperatures, the Bradt Travel Guide also recommended advanced planning for visiting the park.{{Sfn|Bradt|2007|p=345}}

Payment of the entrance fees, renting of the facilities, and hiring of guides, cooks, and porters are handled at either the park headquarters in Andapa or the Park Visitor Center in Manantenina, which is along the main Andapa-Sambava road, {{convert|66|km|mi|abbr=on}} from Sambava and {{convert|40|km|mi|abbr=on}} from Andapa.{{LoM3 Sfn|page=656}}{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|pp=5<U+2013>6}}  The park has a single trail that leads from the information center in Manantenina to the highest peak.{{Sfn|Bradt|2007|p=344}}{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=6}}  The path into the rain forest is divided into three treks that vary in length and lead to each of the three main camps,{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=5}} each of which is situated at different altitudes and offer views of their own distinctive flora and fauna.{{Sfn|Bradt|2007|p=345}}{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|pp=5<U+2013>6}}

[[File:Interpretation Center.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Several people stroll around a room full of exhibits.|Marojejy National Park's visitor center is located in Manantenina.]]
The first section of the path, known as the Mantella Trek, takes visitors just inside the park entrance, and leads to a picnic area after the first  {{convert|2.5|km|mi|abbr=on}}.  The first camp, Camp Mantella, is {{convert|4.5|km|mi|abbr=on}} further along the path.{{LoM3 Sfn|page=656}} The camp is in the lowland rain forest above the Manantenina River at an elevation of {{convert|450|m|ft|abbr=on}}.{{Sfn|Bradt|2007|p=345}}{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=5}}  The camp is {{convert|800|m|ft|abbr=on}} from the Cascade de Humbert waterfall,{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=5}} and offers opportunities to see lemurs, such as the [[northern bamboo lemur]] (''Hapalemur occidentalis'');{{LoM3 Sfn|page=656}} many species of bird, such as the Helmet Vanga; as well as a variety of amphibians and reptiles,{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=5}} such as leaf-tailed geckos, leaf chameleons (genus ''[[Brookesia]]''), and many types of frogs.{{Sfn|Bradt|2007|p=345}}

The next {{convert|2|km|mi|abbr=on}} along the path is known as the Simpona Trek; the name comes from the [[Malagasy language|Malagasy]] name for the silky sifaka, which is found in the area.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=5}}  The trail leads to Camp Marojejia, located at an elevation of {{convert|775|m|ft|abbr=on}} at the transition between lowland and montane rain forest.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=5}}{{LoM3 Sfn|page=656}}{{Sfn|Bradt|2007|pp=345<U+2013>346}}  The camp sits on a mountainside, and its dining area overlooks a forested outcrop of rock, which includes the peak named Ambatotsondrona, or "Leaning Rock".{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=5}}{{Sfn|Bradt|2007|pp=345<U+2013>346}}  This camp is reported to be the best location for spotting the silky sifaka,{{LoM3 Sfn|page=656}} although the staff recommend that visitors hire a specialist tracker to aid in the search.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=5}}

The Marojejy Summit Trek continues up the mountain for another {{convert|2|km|mi|abbr=on}} to Camp Simpona,{{LoM3 Sfn|page=656}} which is in the middle of the moist montane forest at an elevation of {{convert|1250|m|ft|abbr=on}}.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=6}}{{Sfn|Bradt|2007|pp=346<U+2013>347}}  There is a ridge with a viewing platform built on it near the camp.{{Sfn|Bradt|2007|pp=346<U+2013>347}}  Despite the stunted height of the trees in this high-altitude region, silky sifakas can occasionally be spotted from the bungalows.{{LoM3 Sfn|page=656}}{{Sfn|Bradt|2007|pp=346<U+2013>347}}  The [[Rufous-headed Ground-roller]] (''Atelornis crossleyi'') and [[Yellow-bellied Sunbird-asity]] (''Neodrepanis hypoxantha'') can be seen here, and a nearby stream teems with a diverse collection of frog species.{{Sfn|Bradt|2007|pp=346<U+2013>347}}  Camp Simpona also serves as a basecamp for the steep climb to the summit of Marojejy Massif,{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=6}} one of Madagascar's highest but most accessible peaks.{{LoM3 Sfn|page=656}}  The climb to the peak stretches {{convert|2|km|mi|abbr=on}} and takes four to five hours.{{LoM3 Sfn|page=656}}{{Sfn|Bradt|2007|pp=346<U+2013>347}}

