==Local people==
[[File:Malagasy rice planting 01.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Several people (with a woman in the foreground) planting rice on a hillside that has been charred by fire.|Most people in the area surrounding Marojejy National Park are [[Subsistence agriculture|subsistence farmers]]. Many burn hillsides to plant rice ([[slash and burn]] agriculture).]]
The Andapa Basin, surrounded by the high, rugged mountains of Marojejy and Anjanaharibe-Sud, was extremely remote and difficult to access until relatively recently.  As a consequence, the area was not permanently settled until the mid-1800, when refugees fled the [[Merina Kingdom]].  Nearly half a century later, another wave of refugees settled in the area, this time fleeing from French colonists.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=15}}  The population in the region, however, remained relatively small, despite a last small wave of immigration following [[World War I]] when people from [[R<U+00E9>union]] came to the region to grow vanilla.  The population did not increase noticeably until the early 1970s when construction of the Andapa<U+2013>Sambava road was completed, connecting the region to the coast.  This improved transportation route encouraged agricultural development and spawned another wave of immigration.  Over the next 30&nbsp;years, it was estimated that the population tripled, with more than 100,000&nbsp;people living in the region by 2003.{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1452}} With 37&nbsp;villages surrounding Marojejy, the population density is one of the highest in Madagascar and it continues to grow.  The dominant [[Ethnic groups of Madagascar|ethnic groups]] in the region are the [[Tsimihety]] (the first settlers) and the [[Betsimisaraka people|Betsimisaraka]], although other groups from the southern part of the island have also established themselves.{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1452}}{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=15}}

[[File:Malagasy weaving 001.jpg|thumb|left|alt=A Malagasy girls sits on the ground weaving with reeds, while an older gentleman sits on a bench above her.|Fiber for weaving, like many other materials utilized in the traditional lifestyles of the people of the region, is obtained from the forests.]]
The local people have traditionally utilized material from the forest, whether for use in their [[Architecture of Madagascar|architecture]], to make [[pirogue]]s (dugout canoes), to provide fiber for weaving, to provide firewood, to gather leaves for [[traditional medicine]], or to flavor their drinks.  Most of the residents are [[Subsistence agriculture|subsistence rice farmers]] who cultivate irrigated [[Paddy field|paddies]] in valleys or who plant on hillsides that have been cleared and burned ([[slash and burn]] agriculture, known locally as ''tavy'').{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=15}}  The swamps which formerly covered vast areas of Andapa Basin have been converted to rice paddies which are intensively cultivated; however the Tsimihety traditionally practice slash and burn techniques on the hillsides in preference to irrigated rice fields.{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1452}}  Coffee was an important cash crop before market prices fell in the 1970s, but vanilla remains an important crop for the area.  Until the mid-2000s, vanilla prices were high, but they have since fallen off significantly.  The crash of vanilla prices, along with a [[Overpopulation|rapidly growing population]] and steady decrease in cultivatable land, has resulted in widespread and extreme [[poverty]].  Between January and April, before the main rice harvest, many people in the region do not receive enough food to eat.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=15}}  The [[SAVA Region]], which includes Marojejy, is the poorest region in Madagascar, and in 2011, continued [[2007<U+2013>2008 world food price crisis|rises in global food prices]]<U+2014>particularly that of imported rice<U+2014>has made obtaining food more difficult for rural families.<ref name=WorldNews_Rice/>

Not only have international environmental organizations (such as [[Conservation International]], [[Wildlife Conservation Society]], [[World Wide Fund for Nature]], and [[Care International]]) established programs to help local residents, many local people work to improve their situation through environmental and health education programs.  An increase in [[sustainable agriculture]], [[silviculture]], conservation awareness, and improved education and health care have also furthered the goal of protecting the environment and promoting livelihoods centered around the remaining forest.  Limited and responsible ecotourism is also seen as a long-term alternative to continued [[deforestation]].{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=15}}
{{-}}

==Conservation concerns==
The protections normally afforded to [[national park]]s have not halted the degradations of Marojejy National Park.  The hunting of lemurs, including the silky sifaka, is a persistent problem, as is the harvesting of precious hardwoods, such as rosewood and palissandre.  Semi-precious gemstones, such as [[amethyst]], are still mined within the boundaries of the park, while slash and burn agriculture and wood collection for firewood and construction continue to cause the periphery to recede.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=16}}{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1457}}  These pressures are growing strong as the population in the region continues to increase.{{Sfn|Atkinson|Mathieu|2008|p=16}}  In 2003, approximately 200,000 people lived within {{convert|40|km|mi|abbr=on}} of the park, 80% of whom were farmers that were still dependent upon the forest for agricultural land and various products, such as honey, firewood, and plant fibers, as well as tree bark from plants of the family [[Rutaceae]] (primarily genus ''[[Evodia]]'') used to ferment ''betsabetsa'', a local sugarcane spirit.  Additionally, inappropriate use of the park or excessive visitation by guests could also pose a threat to the fragile high-altitude scrub.{{Sfn|Garreau|Manantsara|2003|p=1457}}

===Illegal logging===
{{Main|Illegal logging in Madagascar}}
[[Image:Illegal logging of rosewood 001.jpg|thumb|right|alt=A rosewood stump and adjacent log, both with dark red heartwood, in the forest of Marojejy National Park|Rosewood is illegally logged from Marojejy National Park.]]
Madagascar's northeastern rain forests are severely threatened by [[illegal logging]] of precious hardwood, which not only dries out the forest (making it susceptible to fire), introduces [[invasive species]], [[Habitat destruction|degrades habitat]], and reduces [[genetic diversity]], but also violates local taboos and traditions.{{Sfn|Patel|2007|p=11}}  Additional species, such as species of ''[[Dombeya]]'', are typically cut to make rafts for floating the heavier hardwoods down rivers and out of the parks.{{Sfn|Randriamalala|Liu|2010a|p=13}}  Rosewood trees are cut into multiple logs for easier transport,{{Sfn|Patel|2007|p=12}} and five or more high-buoyancy trees are cut per hardwood log.  To tie the rafts together, the loggers cut thousands of [[liana]]s or vines,{{Sfn|Randriamalala|Liu|2010a|p=13}} which are used by 75% of the forest fauna as avenues for moving around in the canopy.{{Sfn|Randriamalala|Liu|2010a|p=20}}  The logging activities are labor-intensive and dangerous.  The labor employs the impoverished local population, but the officials who facilitate the process primarily benefit.{{Sfn|Patel|2007|p=11}}

[[Image:Illegal export of rosewood 002.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Eight rosewood logs lying at the riverside with nearby workers, a truck, and a cart|Rosewood leaves the park by being floated downstream to waiting trucks.]]
In 2005, illegal logging of rosewood was reported to have occurred more than 20 times.{{Sfn|Patel|2007|p=12}} In 2007 at the port cities of [[Voh<U+00E9>mar]], [[Antalaha]], and [[Toamasina]], authorities confiscated thousands of logs valued at millions of dollars ([[United States dollar|US$]]).  Some of this material was reportedly logged from eastern and northeastern parts of the park.{{Sfn|Patel|2007|p=11}}  At the start of the [[2009 Malagasy political crisis|Malagasy political crisis]] in March 2009, thousands of woodcutters intensely logged precious hardwoods for six to eight weeks in the SAVA Region.{{Sfn|Randriamalala|Liu|2010a|p=12}}  An estimated 52,000&nbsp;tons of rosewood lumber, or nearly 100,000&nbsp;trees, were logged that year, with one-third of the total coming from Marojejy National Park and the remainder from nearby [[Masoala National Park]].{{Sfn|Randriamalala|Liu|2010a|p=11}}  As a result, the park was closed briefly, but reopened in May 2009.{{LoM3 Sfn|page=657}}  In 2010, the situation improved in Marojejy, but illegal logging intensified in Masoala and the [[Makira Natural Park|Makira Protected Area]].{{Sfn|Randriamalala|Liu|2010b|p=32}}

Illegal logging has been facilitated by insufficient governance, unclear forest regulation, and undermined judicial control while the exportation of the acquired logs (in 1992, 2006, and 2009<U+2013>2010) has been permitted by government decrees that either precede elections or are issued during periods of political instability.{{Sfn|Randriamalala|Liu|2010a|p=11}}  The trade is organized and operated by high-ranking officials and influential businessmen.{{Sfn|Patel|2007|p=16}}  Additionally, the trade in Malagasy rosewood is not regulated under the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species ([[CITES]]).{{Sfn|Patel|2007|p=15}}
{{-}}

